As a college student, setting up accounts on GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle felt like a tiny but significant step toward developing my professional identity. Every platform challenges me to consider more carefully how I showcase my abilities, passions, and output to the public.

Because I had to put my academic journey, projects, and goals in writing on LinkedIn rather than just in my head, I became more conscious of them. It helped me realise that networking is something I can begin now by establishing connections with classmates, seniors, and experts in my field. This encouraged me to be more deliberate about the online persona and footprint I leave behind.

Making a Kaggle account served as a reminder that learning data science and machine learning involves more than just theory—it also involves practice and community. Observing actual datasets, notebooks, and competitions helped me assess my current level of proficiency and identify areas for improvement. It inspired me to accept my inexperience, learn from the work of others, and gradually begin offering my own solutions.

However, GitHub gave my coding work a more "real" and long-term feel. Instead of just storing random files on my laptop, I began to think about writing cleaner code, improving documentation, and using version control correctly by putting my projects and experiments there. It also provided me with a place to gradually build a portfolio that I can show to future recruiters, collaborators, or mentors.
